The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Accused duo granted bail
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Accused duo granted bail
  - BOY DROWNING CASE          A STAFF REPORTER                           The two boys being produced at the Juvenile Justice Board on Monday. Picture by Sanat Kumar Sinha                                        
	The two boys held for allegedly drowning 10-year-old Pitu Roy in a Kestopur pond were granted bail by the Juvenile Justice Board on Monday afternoon.         
	Mukulika Sinha, the principal magistrate of the board, released the boys  one eight years old, the other nine  against bonds of Rs 500 each. The officer of Baguiati police station investigating the case was asked to submit reports of the tests to confirm their age. The two will have to appear before the board on June 12.         
	Pitus body was fished out of the pond on May 28 afternoon, three hours after he had gone for a dip with the duo. On May 31, the boys confessed to having drowned their friend after beating him with a wooden stick and stuffing his nose and mouth with mud.        
	Pitus maternal uncle recorded the confession on his video camera. Pitus father later lodged a compliant with the police station and a case was lodged under Section 304 of the IPC  culpable homicide not amounting to murder.        
	On Monday, the magistrate called the boys to her chamber. The father of one of the boys and the mother of the other accompanied them. The boys lawyer Bibhas Chatterjee was also present.         
	The parents stood with folded hands as Sinha asked one of the boys if he knew Pitu was dead. The boy stood silent.        
	Sinha asked the other boy if he knew how to swim. He replied that he didnt. First grow up, learn to swim and then go to the pond. OK? said the magistrate. She asked the first boys mother, a domestic help, to get her son admitted to a school.        
	The summer vacation is on. How can I admit him to school now? she asked. Sinha told her that the admission could wait till schools open.         
	The other boy, whose father is a carpenter, studies in a school.                                                                                                                                                                         
